            "details": {
              "(a) Projection model + circle equation [15]": "15/15 — Correctly sets up the pinhole model with image plane z=-f and derives x=-fX/Z, y=-fY/Z. For a circle on plane Z=Z0 parallel to the image plane, substitutes the parametric circle, shows the projected locus has parametric form x=x_c+r cosθ, y=y_c+r sinθ with x_c=-fX_c/Z0, y_c=-fY_c/Z0, r=-fR/Z0 (and notes r>0 since Z0<0), then eliminates θ to obtain (x-x_c)^2+(y-y_c)^2=r^2. Logic and equations are complete and correct.",
              "(b) Vanishing point + special cases [15]": "14/15 — Derives the vanishing point via limit t→∞ on the projected parametric line, yielding x_v=-f d_x/d_z and y_v=-f d_y/d_z (implicitly assuming d_z≠0; the d_z=0 at-infinity case is discussed later). Provides at least two special-case verifications (planes y=0 and x=0) consistent with the vanishing line/point formulas. Minor issue: the prompt asks special-case discussion in (b), but the report places it later; mathematically it is still correct and sufficiently detailed.",
              "(c) Vanishing line equation [10]": "9/10 — Correctly derives the vanishing line equation Ax_v+By_v+Cf=0 using the plane parallelism constraint Ad_x+Bd_y+Cd_z=0 and the vanishing-point formulas. Collinearity argument is essentially: all vanishing points satisfy the same linear equation, hence lie on a line; this is valid but brief and does not fully expand the geometric/projective reasoning. Overall correct and nearly rigorous.",
